	<h2 id="overview">Overview</h2>
	<p>
		Data Transparency &amp; User Control ensures users can clearly understand how much data a feature consumes,
		what trade-offs are involved, and how to adjust behavior based on their constraints.
	</p>
	<p>
		In low-resource contexts, hidden background usage can quickly break trust. Transparent usage information and
		simple controls make digital services more predictable, usable, and fair.
	</p>

	<h2 id="why-lro">Why this matters for LRO</h2>
	<p>
		For users on costly, unstable, or low-bandwidth networks, uncontrolled data usage can block access to essential
		services. This principle helps teams design for practical realities by ensuring:
	</p>
	<ul class="vf-list vf-list--unordered">
		<li class="vf-list__item">Lower risk of unexpected data costs</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Better continuity when network quality drops</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Improved user trust through clear communication</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Reduced abandonment in high-friction journeys</li>
	</ul>

	<h2 id="key-principles">Key principles</h2>
	<ul class="vf-list vf-list--unordered">
		<li class="vf-list__item"><strong>Be explicit:</strong> show when actions may consume significant data.</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item"><strong>Expose trade-offs:</strong> quality, speed, and data cost should be understandable.</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item"><strong>Give control:</strong> let users choose low-data, balanced, or high-quality modes.</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item"><strong>Remember preferences:</strong> persist user choices safely across sessions.</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item"><strong>Fail safely:</strong> default to low-data behavior under uncertainty.</li>
	</ul>

	<h2 id="what-users-see">What users should see</h2>
	<p>
		Users should receive clear signals about data-impacting actions before they commit.
	</p>
	<ul class="vf-list vf-list--unordered">
		<li class="vf-list__item">Estimated download size for heavy resources</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Whether media auto-plays, streams, or preloads</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">When background sync or polling is active</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Current mode label, such as Low Data Mode</li>
	</ul>

	<h2 id="what-users-control">What users should control</h2>
	<p>
		Controls should be visible, simple, and reversible.
	</p>
	<ul class="vf-list vf-list--unordered">
		<li class="vf-list__item">Media quality selection (low, standard, high)</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Autoplay and preload behavior</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Background refresh frequency</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Image loading preference for metered connections</li>
	</ul>
	<pre class="vf-code-example__pre"><code>&lt;button data-mode="low"&gt;Low data&lt;/button&gt;
&lt;button data-mode="balanced"&gt;Balanced&lt;/button&gt;
&lt;button data-mode="high"&gt;High quality&lt;/button&gt;</code></pre>

	<h2 id="ui-patterns">UI patterns in constrained environments</h2>
	<h3>Prompt at decision points</h3>
	<p>
		Ask for consent before large transfers, such as video playback or archive downloads.
	</p>
	<h3>Progressive reveal of heavy assets</h3>
	<p>
		Load text summaries first, then offer an explicit "load full media" action.
	</p>
	<h3>Preference-first defaults</h3>
	<p>
		If connection quality is unknown, start in low-data mode and allow opt-in upgrades.
	</p>

	<h2 id="implementation">Implementation guidance</h2>
	<h3>1. Detect likely constraints</h3>
	<pre class="vf-code-example__pre"><code>const prefersReducedData = window.matchMedia('(prefers-reduced-data: reduce)').matches;
const conn = navigator.connection;
const isConstrained = prefersReducedData || (conn && ['slow-2g', '2g', '3g'].includes(conn.effectiveType));</code></pre>

	<h3>2. Apply low-data defaults</h3>
	<ul class="vf-list vf-list--unordered">
		<li class="vf-list__item">Defer non-critical scripts and images</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Disable autoplay by default</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Serve compressed or lower-resolution assets first</li>
	</ul>

	<h3>3. Persist explicit user choice</h3>
	<pre class="vf-code-example__pre"><code>function setDataMode(mode) {
	localStorage.setItem('dataMode', mode);
	document.documentElement.dataset.dataMode = mode;
}</code></pre>

	<h3>4. Communicate active mode</h3>
	<p>
		Add a compact status indicator so users always know whether low-data behavior is active.
	</p>

	<h2 id="pitfalls">Common pitfalls</h2>
	<ul class="vf-list vf-list--unordered">
		<li class="vf-list__item">Hiding controls deep in settings pages</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Using technical language instead of user-centered wording</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Ignoring user preference after app restart</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Loading heavy third-party scripts regardless of selected mode</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Providing control but not measurable feedback</li>
	</ul>

	<h2 id="dos-donts">Do / Don't</h2>
	<h4>Do</h4>
	<ul class="vf-list vf-list--unordered">
		<li class="vf-list__item">Label data-heavy actions before execution</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Offer obvious low-data controls near content</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Persist mode selection and respect it consistently</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Test degraded behavior on constrained networks</li>
	</ul>

	<h4>Don't</h4>
	<ul class="vf-list vf-list--unordered">
		<li class="vf-list__item">Assume all users can afford high-quality defaults</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Auto-load large media without warning</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Reset user preference silently</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Tie essential tasks to high-bandwidth features</li>
	</ul>

	<h2 id="checklist">Checklist</h2>
	<ul class="vf-list vf-list--unordered">
		<li class="vf-list__item">Large actions include clear data-impact messaging</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Low-data mode is easy to discover and toggle</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">User preference is persisted and applied globally</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Heavy assets can be deferred or replaced with summaries</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Behavior remains usable under slow-2g/2g/3g simulations</li>
	</ul>

	<h2 id="metrics-tools">Metrics &amp; tools</h2>
	<p>
		Track these outcomes to verify impact in production:
	</p>
	<ul class="vf-list vf-list--unordered">
		<li class="vf-list__item">Average transferred bytes per session</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Completion rate by connection profile</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Opt-in rate for low-data mode</li>
		<li class="vf-list__item">Bounce rate for data-heavy journeys</li>
	</ul>
	<p>
		Useful tools include Chrome Lighthouse, WebPageTest, and Network Information API diagnostics.
	</p>

